The ongoing registration for the 2020 Joint Admission and Matriculation Board (JAMB) examination, scheduled to last from January 13-February 17 has been hampered by bad network connection in Abia State. Speaking to newsmen after monitoring the exercise at some registration centres in Umuahia, the state capital, the chairman of the governing council of the JAMB, Dr. Emmanuel Ndukwe expressed displeasure over the development. Ndukwe said he had complained over the matter to the director of Information Communication Technology (ICT) at the JAMB Headquarters, Abuja, assuring that adequate attention was being accorded to it. He explained that he was impressed with the turnout of applicants for the registration, appealing to both them and operators of the centres to be patient with the interruption and delay. At the Directorate of ICT, Michael Okpara University of Agriculture (MOUAU), the head, Network Management, Mr Sunny Eyeh said out of the 1,500 anticipated registrations, they had completed over 700. Eyeh, who said the interruption has been stressful on both the staff and the applicants especially those from outside Umuahia, added that they had notified and received assurance from JAMB that it will soon be over. Miss Faith told LEADERSHIP Friday at XYZ Technology Centre, New Secretariat, Umuahia that it took her about three hours from the time she arrived the centre to complete the registration. Receiving Ndukwe in his office in Ubakala earlier, the state JAMB coordinator, Mr Chidebe Achunine, said the staff had been working round the clock to ensure the timely and successful completion of the exercise.